    78‚Üí## Other Use Cases
    79‚Üí
    80‚Üí### Load configuration without altering the environment
    81‚Üí
    82‚ÜíThe function `dotenv_values` works more or less the same way as `load_dotenv`,
    83‚Üíexcept it doesn't touch the environment, it just returns a `dict` with the
    84‚Üívalues parsed from the `.env` file.
    85‚Üí
    86‚Üí```python
    87‚Üífrom dotenv import dotenv_values
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üíconfig = dotenv_values(".env")  # config = {"USER": "foo", "EMAIL": "foo@example.org"}
    90‚Üí```
    91‚Üí
    92‚ÜíThis notably enables advanced configuration management:
    93‚Üí
    94‚Üí```python
    95‚Üíimport os
    96‚Üífrom dotenv import dotenv_values
    97‚Üí
    98‚Üíconfig = {
    99‚Üí    **dotenv_values(".env.shared"),  # load shared development variables
   100‚Üí    **dotenv_values(".env.secret"),  # load sensitive variables
   101‚Üí    **os.environ,  # override loaded values with environment variables
   102‚Üí}
   103‚Üí```
   104‚Üí
   105‚Üí### Parse configuration as a stream
   106‚Üí
   107‚Üí`load_dotenv` and `dotenv_values` accept [streams][python_streams] via their
   108‚Üí`stream` argument. It is thus possible to load the variables from sources other
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   120‚Üí### Load .env files in IPython
   121‚Üí
   122‚ÜíYou can use dotenv in IPython. By default, it will use `find_dotenv` to search for a
   123‚Üí`.env` file:
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   141‚Üí### Disable load_dotenv
   142‚Üí
   143‚ÜíSet `PYTHON_DOTENV_DISABLED=1` to disable `load_dotenv()` from loading .env
   144‚Üífiles or streams. Useful when you can't modify third-party package calls or in
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   147‚Üí## Command-line Interface
   148‚Üí
   149‚ÜíA CLI interface `dotenv` is also included, which helps you manipulate the `.env`
   150‚Üífile without manually opening it.
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
